[{"type":"{{","value":[["pagebanner"],["Mena-asia_default_banner.jpg"],["pgname=Niigata"]]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Image:Japan_niigata_map_small.png"],["right"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"'''","value":["Niigata prefecture"]}," (新潟県 ",{"type":"''","value":["Niigata-ken"]},") ",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.pref.niigata.jp\/sougouseisaku\/kokusai\/english\/"]}," is on the Japan Sea coast of the central ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Chubu"]]}," region of ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Japan"]]},".\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Understand"]},"\nNiigata was formerly divided into the provinces of ",{"type":"'''","value":["Echigo"]}," (越後), on the mainland, and ",{"type":"'''","value":["Sado"]}," (佐渡), a large island off the coast.\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["Further reading"]},"\n",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.trafford.com\/04-2705 My Mother is a Tractor"]},", by Nicholas Klar. A former English teacher with a witty and informative take on Japanese society. Written from the depths of the Niigata countryside.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Cities"]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Image:Japan Niigata Pref Map.png"],["thumb"],["350px"],["Niigata Pref Map"]]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":["Kaetsu Region(下越地方)"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Niigata"]]}," — the prefectural capital. "]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Murakami"]]}," — castle town which is famous for hotsprings and salmon."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Shibata"]]}," — castle town which is famous for Tsukioka Onsen."]},{"type":"'''","value":["Chuetsu Region(中越地方)"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Nagaoka"]]},"  — the second largest city in the prefecture"]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Kashiwazaki"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Izumozaki"]]}," — Small town.birth place of the 18th century monk-poet Ryōkan."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Minami-Uonuma"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Sanjo"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tokamachi"]]}," — famous for its snow festival, the first in Japan."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yuzawa (Niigata)"],["Yuzawa"]]}," — popular spa and ski resort"]},{"type":"'''","value":["Joetsu Region(上越地方)"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Joetsu"]]}," — train hub also featuring the port of Naoetsu"]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Itoigawa"]]}," — famous for Itoigawa Geopark."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Myoko"]]}," - well known for its onsen and great skiing. Nearby Lake Nojiri is also a popular summer retreat."]},{"type":"'''","value":["Sado Island(佐渡島)"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Sado"],["Sado"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["Other destinations"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Sado Island"]]}," — with a tragic history of exiles and slave labor gold mines, now known for its scenic beauty and a large music festival"]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Joshin'etsukogen National Park"]]}," - the second largest national park in japan."]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Oze National Park"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get in"]},"\t\n",{"type":"===","value":["By plane"]},"\nNiigata Airport handles international flights from Korea (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Seoul"]]}," daily on Korean Air), China (",{"type":"[[","value":[["Shanghai"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Xian"]]}," three times weekly on China Eastern, ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Harbin"]]}," four times weekly on China Southern), and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Guam"]]}," (twice weekly on Continental). There are also frequent domestic flights from ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Osaka"]]}," (¥25,100 one way), ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Sapporo"]]}," (¥28,700 one way), ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Fukuoka"]]}," (¥31,700 one way), and other cities. The prefectural government has produced an airport guide (",{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.niigata-airport.gr.jp\/?lang=en"]},"), which may be useful.\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By train"]},"\nThe ",{"type":"'''","value":["Joetsu Shinkansen"]}," line connects ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Niigata (city)"],["Niigata"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tokyo"]]}," in around 2 hours, passing through ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yuzawa (Niigata)"],["Yuzawa"]]}," on the way.\nAlternatively, the ",{"type":"'''","value":["Nagano Shinkansen"]}," line connects ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Nagano (city)"],["Nagano"]]}," to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tokyo"]]}," also in around 2 hours. From Nagano one can take an express or local train onwards to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Myoko"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Joetsu"]]}," in Niigata Prefecture\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get around"]},"\t \n\n",{"type":"==","value":["See"]},"\nEvery year, around the last ten days of July, there is a big fireworks display in Kashiwazaki, which is well-known for the ones which are shot off over the Japan Sea. Moreover, the number of the fireworks shot off there is about 15,000 shots and those are so beautiful.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Do"]},"\t \nNiigata is the heart of Japan's ",{"type":"'''","value":["Snow Country"]},", which means it's a great place for skiing (see above destinations).\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Eat"]},"\t \nNiigata is famed for its ",{"type":"''","value":["koshihikari"]}," rice, generally considered one of the best grades in the country.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Drink"]},"\t \nThanks to its famous rice and abundance of mountain streams, Niigata produces some of the best ",{"type":"'''","value":["sake"]}," in the country including famous labels like ",{"type":"'''","value":["Kubota"]}," (久保田), ",{"type":"'''","value":["Koshinokanbai"]}," (越乃寒梅) and ",{"type":"'''","value":["Hakkaisan"]}," (八海山).\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Go next"]},"\t \n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Yamagata (prefecture)"],["Yamagata Prefecture"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Fukushima (prefecture)"],["Fukushima Prefecture"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Tochigi (prefecture)"],["Tochigi Prefecture"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Gunma"],["Gunma Prefecture"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Nagano (prefecture)"],["Nagano Prefecture"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Toyama (prefecture)"],["Toyama Prefecture"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["outlineregion"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["geo"],["37.6167"],["138.8667"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["IsPartOf"],["Chubu"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["WikiPedia:Niigata Prefecture"]]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Dmoz:Regional\/Asia\/Japan\/Prefectures\/Niigata\/"]]},"\n\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["Commons:Category:Niigata Prefecture"]]}]